  "local_port": 40392,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "I am repairing a soft steel chair by arc welding and keep burning holes in the metal, what can I do to make a strong joint?",
  "response": "Burning holes in the metal while arc welding can be frustrating and typically results from too much heat input, high amperage, incorrect travel speed, improper technique, or poorly prepared surfaces. Here are some steps you can take to improve your welding technique and achieve a strong joint without burning holes:\n\n1. **Use the Right Electrode**: Ensure you are using the correct type and size of electrode for the thickness of the metal you are welding. For soft steel, ER70S-6 is a common choice.\n\n2. **Adjust Your Settings**: \n   - **Amperage**: Make sure your amperage is appropriate for the thickness of the material. For thinner materials, reduce the amperage.\n   - **Voltage**: Ensure the voltage setting is compatible with the electrode type and welding position.\n   - **Wire Feed Speed**: Check the wire feed speed if you are using a MIG welder, as too high a feed speed can lead to excess heat.\n\n3. **Control Heat Input**: Use a stitch welding technique or a weaving motion to distribute heat more evenly. Avoid staying in one spot for too long to prevent burning through.\n\n4. **Travel Speed**: Move your welding torch or electrode at a consistent and appropriate speed. If you move too slowly, you'll generate too much heat, resulting in holes.\n\n5. **Use Backing Bars**: If possible, place a backing bar or plate behind the joint being welded to support the weld pool and absorb excess heat.\n\n6. **Proper Fit-Up**: Ensure that the parts to be welded are properly fitted and aligned. Gaps can lead to excessive burn-through.\n\n7. **Clean the Material**: Make sure the surfaces are clean and free of rust, paint, or other contaminants that can affect the weld quality.\n\n8. **Weld in the Right Position**: Welding on a flat position can be easier for beginners compared to vertical or overhead positions, which require more skill.\n\n9. **Tack Welds**: Consider making tack welds to hold the parts in place before doing a continuous weld. This maintains alignment and can prevent warping.\n\n10. **Practice**: If you're new to welding or trying a new technique, practice on scrap pieces of soft steel before tackling the actual work.\n\nBy following these suggestions, you should be able to make strong joints without burning holes in the metal. Patience and practice will help you improve your welding skills.",
